What - used to be like - what my father used to take prints off the - people used to put the prints on the plates and the cups and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7999576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6713198\charrsid14555338 Is that like what you'd call lithographers now?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid810202 ER  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6713198\charrsid14555338 No. No,
 it isn't lithographing, this is the transferrer. Transferrer and lithographing are two different trades altogether. In - in lithographing you put your own prints on, which you do in transferring but they have to be taken off - by a man first with a steam
 
roll - with a - a rolling machine, a big machine and they used to come through all there see, and they used to have a - a girl to cut the prints and then all them prints were given to so many people. And they had to cut them. Very much like lithographing 
but it isn't lithographing. Lithographing's done on glass ware. This was done on basic ware.
